               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WOOLLETT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491029-name-1089" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1089" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1089" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1089" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>JANE JONES</persName>
                  </hi>. I am single, and reside at Langford, Somersetshire. I know the prisoner and Mary Parsons—she is my cousin—I was present when they were married—I believe it was four years ago, but I am not quite sure about the date—I have no doubt the prisoner is the person—I believe the marriage was at St. John's Church, Bristol, but I am not sure.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491029-name-1090" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1090" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1090" type="surname" value="LIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1090" type="given" value="PHOEBE SOPHIA"></interp>PHÅ’BE SOPHIA LIGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, and reside at Clifton. I remember Mary Parsons being married in 1845, to a person named Purnell—the prisoner is that person, they returned after the wedding to my house to breakfast—I saw Mary Parsons last week.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491029-name-1091" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1091" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1091" type="surname" value="LUCAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1091" type="given" value="MARY ELIZABETH"></interp>MARY ELIZABETH LUCAS</persName>
                  </hi>. I resided at Tylehurst. I was married in June, 1849, to the prisoner, in the name of James Richardson, at Christ Church, Surrey—I believed at the time he was a single man; he told me so.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> In what name were we lodging at the time of our marriage? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In the name of Smith; I first became acquainted with you, I believe, in Nov., 1848, or a little before that; I did not know you were married till after I married you; I came to your house twice on business; I did not then see a person who I believed was Mrs. Purnell; I saw a person who you denied was Mrs. Purnell; you were living with her as a wife, and had got one child by her; I agreed to stand godmother for that child.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you live with the prisoner before you married him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; a short time, not longer than a month; we lived in the name of Mr. and Mrs. Smith—that was under a promise of marriage—I did not know the woman 1 saw was his wife.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491029-name-1092" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1092" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1092" type="surname" value="AYLETTE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1092" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>ALFRED AYLETTE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman</hi>). I produce two certificates; the first is of a marriage in 1845, at St. James', Bristol, on 22d Sept., between John Pur<lb></lb>nell</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184910290189"></xptr>
               <p>and Mary Parsons, and the second of a marriage at Christ Church, Surrey, on 12th June, 1849, between James Richardson and Mary Elizabeth Lucas—I have compared them with the originals myself, and find them to be true copies.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> Lucas knew I was married; she has several times drank tea with me and my wife; about a week before we left Reading, to live together as man and wife in London, she gave me 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for the purpose of send<lb></lb>ing my wife home on a visit, that she might be absent, and I have a letter of hers which proves she was fully aware I was married—(<hi rend="italic">the witness, Lucas, stating that this letter was her writing, the prisoner read it</hi>—it commenced, "Miss Lucas will not be able to call on Mrs. Purnell this afternoon, in con<lb></lb>sequence of the dampness of the weather, &amp;c. &amp;c.")—after she had lived with me two months, she became anxious of satisfying her friends that she was not living in a state of prostitution, but was a married woman; she became desirous of having a certificate to send to her friends; she said nothing could be done to prosecute me without her, and the least I could do, was to give her the opportunity of satisfying them, and I married her in the name of Richardson.</p>
